{{Infobox book| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Waffen-SS in Action | title_orig = Waffen-SS im Einsatz | image = [[File:Book cover of Waffen SS im Einsatz by Paul Hausser.jpg|130px]] | caption = | author = [[Paul Hausser]] | cover_artist = | country = [[West Germany]] | language = German | series = | genre = War story; [[Historical revisionism (negationism)|Historical revisionism]] | publisher = {{Illm|Plesse Verlag|de|Plesse-Verlag}} | release_date = 1953 | media_type = Print | pages = | isbn = | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = Soldiers Like Any Other }}
'''''Waffen-SS im Einsatz ''''' (''Waffen-SS in Action'') is a 1953 book in German by [[Paul Hausser]], a former high-ranking [[Waffen-SS]] member and a leader of the Waffen-SS lobby group [[HIAG]]. As part of the organisation's [[Historical revisionism (negationism)|revisionist]] agenda, it advanced the idea of the purely military role of the Waffen-SS.{{sfn|Simpson|1990}}
The first major work by one of the HIAG leaders, it was published by {{Illm|Plesse Verlag|de|Plesse-Verlag}}, owned by a right-wing politician and publisher {{illm|Waldemar Schütz|de|Waldemar Schütz}}. Hausser's book, along with those by other key HIAG members [[Felix Steiner]] and [[Kurt Meyer]], has been characterised by the historian Charles Sydnor as one of the "most important works of [Waffen-SS] apologist literature."{{sfn|Sydnor|1990|p=319}}
== Background == From 1950, Hausser was active in [[HIAG]], a [[Historical revisionism (negationism)|revisionist]] organization and a [[advocacy group|lobby group]] of former [[Waffen-SS]] members. HIAG began in late 1950 as a loose association of local groups; by October 1951, it claimed to have 376 local branches. In December 1951, Hausser became its first spokesperson.{{sfn|Large|1987|pp=82–83}}
As part of its lobbying efforts, HIAG attempted to advance the idea of the Waffen-SS being the "fourth branch of the [[Wehrmacht]]" and in no way connected to the crimes of the regime.{{sfn|Large|1987|p=81}} HIAG's rewriting of history included significant multi-prong [[Propaganda|propaganda efforts]], including tendentious periodicals, books and public speeches, along with a publishing house – [[Munin Verlag]] – to serve as a platform for its publicity aims. The express aim of Munin Verlag was to publish the "war narratives" of former Waffen-SS members, in cooperation with HIAG.{{sfn|Wilke|2011|p=399}}{{sfn|MacKenzie|1997|p=138}}
== Contents == British [[military history|military historian]] [[Keith Simpson (politician)|Keith Simpson]] in his book ''Waffen SS'' quotes Hausser for writing that, he "hoped the work would disperse the lies and calumnies which had formed themselves around the Waffen-SS and help to give this courageous formation its place."{{sfn|Simpson|1990|p=6}} The book had an unmistakable connection to the Nazi origins of the Waffen-SS: the SS runes on the cover art and the SS motto ("my honor is my loyalty") embossed on the cloth cover. A foreword from the former Wehrmacht general [[Hans Guderian]] provided an endorsement for the Waffen-SS troops and referred to them as "the first realization of the European idea".{{sfn|MacKenzie|1997|pp=137–138}}
The book described the growth of Waffen-SS into a so-called multinational force where foreign volunteers fought heroically as a "militant example of the great European idea".{{sfn|MacKenzie|1997|pp=137–138}} Historians have refuted this characterisation, arguing that it was largely Nazi propaganda employed to bolster the ranks of the Waffen-SS with foreign volunteers. The message was later repurposed by HIAG as it sought historical and legal rehabilitation of the force.{{sfn|MacKenzie|1997|pp=137–138}}
Hausser wrote another book, published in 1966 by HIAG's imprint {{illm|Munin Verlag|de|Munin-Verlag}}, under the title ''Soldaten wie andere auch'' ("Soldiers Like Any Other"). According to the military historian [[Simon MacKenzie|S.P. MacKenzie]], the work epitomised how HIAG leaders wanted the Waffen-SS to be remembered, while the historian Charles Sydnor described it as "equally tendentious".{{sfn|MacKenzie|1997|p=137}}{{sfn|Sydnor|1973}}
== Reception == ''Waffen-SS in Action'' was included in the index of objectionable war books maintained by West Germany's [[Federal Department for Media Harmful to Young Persons]]. The index was created in the early 1960s to limit the sale of such works to minors due to their chauvinism and glorification of violence.{{sfn|Tauber Volume I|1967|p=539}}
Hausser's books, along with those by other key HIAG members and former Waffen-SS generals [[Felix Steiner]] and [[Kurt Meyer]], have been characterised by the historian Charles Sydnor as the "most important works of [Waffen-SS] apologist literature." These works demanded rehabilitation of the military branch of the Nazi Party and presented Waffen-SS members as both victims and misunderstood heroes.{{sfn|Sydnor|1990|p=319}}
